return (
<>
<Summary expenses={expenses} />
<ExpenseList expenses={expenses} />
</>
);
When the app runs for the first time, React:

Renders <Summary /> and <ExpenseList />

Gives them an empty list [] as the expenses prop

2ï¸âƒ£ Updating State
Now you add a new item using:

js
Copy
Edit
setExpenses([...expenses, newExpense]);
This updates the expenses state.

ğŸ§  React keeps track of state changes. When it sees that expenses changed, it re-runs the App component.

3ï¸âƒ£ React Re-renders the Whole Component Function
React re-runs this:

jsx
Copy
Edit
return (
<>
<Summary expenses={expenses} />
<ExpenseForm onAdd={addExpense} />
<ExpenseList expenses={expenses} />
</>
);
This time:

expenses is not empty anymore

The new list is passed into Summary and ExpenseList

React calls (re-renders) those components with updated props

ğŸª„ Magic? No â€” Just Reactâ€™s Reconciliation!
React uses a smart system called the virtual DOM. It figures out what changed, and only re-renders the parts of the UI that need it â€” like ExpenseList and Summary.

ğŸ“¦ TL;DR
â“ â€œIf I update expenses, do Summary and ExpenseList get called again?â€

âœ… Yes â€” React automatically re-renders them with the new data, because you're passing expenses as a prop, and that prop changed.

